Bike Sharing Demand (kaggle)-Forecast use of a city bikeshare system¶

Argyrios Georgiadis¶

January 2022¶

Introduction¶

The dataset has been taken from https://www.kaggle.com/c/bike-sharing-demand/data

and included the following columns:
datetime - hourly date + timestamp

season - 1 = spring, 2 = summer, 3 = fall, 4 = winter
holiday - whether the day is considered a holiday
workingday - whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday
weather - 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog
temp - temperature in Celsius
atemp - "feels like" temperature in Celsius
humidity - relative humidity
windspeed - wind speed
casual - number of non-registered user rentals initiated
registered - number of registered user rentals initiated
count - number of total rentals

#extract year, month, hour and drop datetime column
bikes['year']=bikes['datetime'].str.slice(3,4).astype(int)
bikes['month']=bikes['datetime'].str.slice(5,7).astype(int)
bikes['hour']=bikes['datetime'].str.slice(11,13).astype(int)
bikes = bikes.drop(columns = ['datetime'])

#get dummies from weather column, standarize temp, humidity and windspeed columns
bikes_copy = pd.get_dummies(bikes_copy, columns=['weather'], drop_first = True)
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

col_names = ["temp", "humidity","windspeed"]
features = bikes_copy[col_names]
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(features.values)
features = scaler.transform(features.values)

bikes_copy[col_names] = features

In [6]:
# Create arrays for the features and the response variable
y = bikes_copy['count'].values
X = bikes_copy.drop('count', axis=1).values

#split data in train and test
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,
test_size = 0.3, random_state=42)

Fit data with several models¶

Below, I fit the data with several models, calculate the time it takes the models to run, calculate the RMSE for each model, plot for all models for comparison reasons. Select features with different methods. Finally, in some cases I tuned the models hyperparameters for best fitting

In [7]:
#create a linear regression model and fit for train data 
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error as MSE
import time
start_time = time.time()
LinReg = LinearRegression()
LinReg.fit(X_train, y_train)
#predict for test data and calculate score 
y_pred_LinReg = LinReg.predict(X_test)
rmse_LinReg = MSE(y_test, y_pred_LinReg)**(1/2)
end_time = time.time()
time_LinReg = end_time - start_time
print('Test set RMSE of LinReg: {:.2f}'.format(rmse_LinReg))
print("Result calculated in {:.5f} sec".format(time_LinReg))

Test set RMSE of LinReg: 141.05
Result calculated in 0.02491 sec

print('Test set RMSE of Lasso: {:.2f}'.format(rmse_lasso))

Test set RMSE of Lasso: 142.39

#fit the data with a Decision Tree Regressor
# Import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
# Define the grid of hyperparameters 'params_dt'
params_dt = {
'max_depth': [2, 5,10],
'max_features': [0.2, 0.4,0.6, 0.8]
}

dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42)

grid_dt = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt,
param_grid=params_dt,
cv=5)

# Fit 'grid_dt' to the training data
grid_dt.fit(X_train, y_train)

best_hyperparams = grid_dt.best_params_
print('Best hyerparameters:\n', best_hyperparams)

Best hyerparameters:
 {'max_depth': 10, 'max_features': 0.8}

Seems like the time it takes for a model to run is not always the same. In general though we can say that the regression models seem to be faster and the rf and dt seem to have lower error.

Models with less features¶

Based on the several feature charts above, I reduce the model features to 5 and try to calculate again the time and the RMSE. I compared those values with the initial models with all features.

The models used are:
model 1 : 'hour','temp','humidity','month','year','count' (as suggested by lasso and kbest)
model 2 : 'hour','temp','workingday','season','year','count' (as suggested by dt)
model 3 : 'hour','temp','workingday','month','year','count' (as suggested by rf)

I fit the models with linear regression and dt below.

Summary¶

In this project, I explored a bike sharing demand dataset. I used several models to predict the number of bikes rented. I reduced the features used in the model from 12 to 5. Those more simple models has similar rmse with more complicated models and are in some cases faster.
